{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_Vaep2DMUrFtUPNQ5Clgp5Uor","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Prompt Writing Guide\n2\t\n3\tA prompt is a markdown file that tells the YOLO agent what to build. Each prompt produces one atomic, verifiable change.\n4\t\n5\t## When to Write a Prompt\n6\t\n7\t**This document does NOT decide direct vs prompt vs spec.** That decision lives in [../choosing-a-flow.md](../choosing-a-flow.md) — the single source of truth. Read it first to confirm a prompt is the right flow.\n8\t\n9\tIn short: write a prompt when the change is a code change that does NOT carry a business-level \"why\" that deserves its own document. Markdown / docs / configs / small operator scripts → direct edits, not prompts. Features with a real business-why → spec first. See the canonical decision doc.\n10\t\n11\tYou may also write prompts manually for finer control over decomposition from an approved spec (the daemon does this automatically by default).\n12\t\n13\t## Creating a Prompt\n14\t\n15\tUse the Claude Code command:\n16\t\n17\t```\n18\t/dark-factory:create-prompt\n19\t```\n20\t\n21\tOr create manually. Location depends on status and project config:\n22\t\n23\t| Status | Directory | Purpose |\n24\t|--------|-----------|---------|\n25\t| `idea` | `prompts/ideas/` | Rough concepts, not ready for approval |\n26\t| `draft` | inbox dir (default: `prompts/`) | Complete prompts, ready for review and approval |\n27\t\n28\tThe inbox directory is configurable per project. Run `dark-factory config` to check the actual `inboxDir` path before writing prompts.\n29\t\n30\t```bash\n31\t# Check your project's inbox directory\n32\tdark-factory config | grep inboxDir\n33\t\n34\t# Idea — park it for later\n35\ttouch prompts/ideas/my-change.md\n36\t\n37\t# Draft — ready for review (use the inboxDir from config)\n38\ttouch prompts/my-change.md\n39\t```\n40\t\n41\tUse lowercase-kebab-case. Dark-factory assigns execution numbers on approve (e.g., `248-spec-044-model.md`).\n42\t\n43\t**Ordering prefix for dependent prompts.** When multiple prompts must execute in strict order, prefix with a simple number to define the sequence: `1-spec-044-model.md`, `2-spec-044-executor-timeout.md`, `3-spec-044-processor-retry.md`. Approve them in order — dark-factory replaces the prefix with execution numbers. Do NOT number standalone prompts.\n44\t\n45\t## Prompt Structure\n46\t\n47\t### Frontmatter\n48\t\n49\t```yaml\n50\t---\n51\tstatus: draft\n52\t---\n53\t```\n54\t\n55\tWhen linking to a spec:\n56\t\n57\t```yaml\n58\t---\n59\tspec: [\"030-foo-bar-baz\"]\n60\tstatus: draft\n61\tcreated: \"2026-03-11T10:00:00Z\"\n62\t---\n63\t```\n64\t\n65\t- `spec` must be a YAML array of strings — single or multiple entries\n66\t- **Canonical form is the full slug** (e.g. `[\"030-foo-bar-baz\"]`), not the bare number. Daemon-generated prompts use this form, and `pkg/slugmigrator` rewrites bare numbers to full slugs after each generation cycle so all prompts converge on the canonical form\n67\t- Bare numbers (`spec: [\"030\"]`) are accepted as input — the slug migrator resolves them to the full form at the next daemon iteration\n68\t- Only use `spec`, `status`, `created`, `issue` — dark-factory adds the rest\n69\t- Valid inbox statuses: `idea` (rough concept, needs refinement) or `draft` (complete, ready for approval)\n70\t\n71\t### Body\n72\t\n73\t```xml\n74\t<summary>\n75\t5-10 bullet points describing WHAT this prompt achieves, not HOW.\n76\tWritten for human review — no file paths, no struct names.\n77\t\n78\tGOOD:\n79\t- Projects can configure a validation command for all prompts\n80\t- The command's exit code determines success or failure\n81\t- Existing prompts continue to work unchanged\n82\t\n83\tBAD:\n84\t- Adds `validationCommand` field to `Config` in `pkg/config/config.go`\n85\t- Calls `exec.Command` in `pkg/executor/executor.go`\n86\t</summary>\n87\t\n88\t<objective>\n89\tWhat to build and why (1-3 sentences). State the end state, not the steps.\n90\t</objective>\n91\t\n92\t<context>\n93\tRead CLAUDE.md for project conventions.\n94\tRead `pkg/config/config.go` — find the `Config` struct and `Validate` method.\n95\t</context>\n96\t\n97\t<requirements>\n98\t1. Specific, numbered, unambiguous steps\n99\t2. Include exact file paths (repo-relative, not absolute)\n100\t3. Include function/type names as anchors (not line numbers)\n101\t4. Show old → new code patterns where helpful\n102\t</requirements>\n103\t\n104\t<constraints>\n105\t- Do NOT commit — dark-factory handles git\n106\t- Existing tests must still pass\n107\t- [Copy constraints from spec — agent has no memory between prompts]\n108\t</constraints>\n109\t\n110\t<verification>\n111\tRun `make precommit` -- must pass.\n112\t</verification>\n113\t```\n114\t\n115\t## Writing Rules\n116\t\n117\t### Specificity over brevity — but pick the right *kind* of specificity\n118\t\n119\tLonger, more specific prompts succeed more often *when the specificity is about contracts and anchors*, not when it's about pre-deciding every line of code the agent will write. Spelling out every if/else and every error message ships the author's bugs verbatim and prevents the agent from applying existing project conventions. See [Detail Levels](#detail-levels) below for how to pick the right grain.\n120\t\n121\tAlways include:\n122\t- Exact file paths (repo-relative)\n123\t- Function/type names as primary anchors\n124\t- Library import paths\n125\t- References to existing files demonstrating each pattern the new code follows\n126\t\n127\tOptional (depends on detail level):\n128\t- Line numbers only as hints (`~line 176`) — go stale quickly\n129\t- Old → new code patterns for find-and-replace — useful for mechanical refactors, harmful for novel work\n130\t- Inlined code bodies — see Detail Levels for when this helps vs. hurts\n131\t\n132\t### Detail Levels\n133\t\n134\tPrompts span a spectrum from \"fully scripted\" to \"intent only.\" Each level has real trade-offs. Pick deliberately; default to **Level 3 (Medium)** for most work in a mature codebase. Mismatched grain is the most common cause of prompt failure: too much detail ships author bugs, too little produces wrong abstractions.\n135\t\n136\t| Level | Shape | Typical line count |\n137\t|-------|-------|-------------------|\n138\t| 1 — Very Detailed | Full inlined function bodies, every `if`/`else` written, error messages pre-decided | 500–1500 |\n139\t| 2 — Detailed | Function signatures + key error paths inlined; agent fills bodies | 200–500 |\n140\t| 3 — Medium *(default)* | Interfaces + sequence + pattern references + failure modes; no function bodies | 80–200 |\n141\t| 4 — Soft | End-state contracts + pattern references; agent chooses structure | 40–100 |\n142\t| 5 — Very Rough | One-paragraph intent + verification command | 10–40 |\n143\t\n144\t#### Level 1 — Very Detailed (scripted)\n145\t\n146\t**Shape:** Full Go source inlined for every function. Every conditional written out. Test cases enumerated by literal value.\n147\t\n148\t**Pros:**\n149\t- Maximum reproducibility across model versions; works on cheap/weak models.\n150\t- The exact output is in the prompt — no agent interpretation needed.\n151\t- Good for teaching examples or documenting a canonical implementation.\n152\t\n153\t**Cons:**\n154\t- The author's bugs ship verbatim (the agent faithfully implements the wrong `fmt.Errorf` instead of the project's `errors.Wrapf`).\n155\t- Drifts from project style because the prompt-author writes from memory, not from existing code.\n156\t- Audit becomes line-by-line code review of the prompt — slow and error-prone.\n157\t- The agent's pattern-matching strength is wasted.\n158\t- Any reusable knowledge inside the prompt rots and re-rots across every future prompt that needs the same pattern.\n159\t\n160\t**When to use:**\n161\t- Brand-new pattern with no existing exemplar in the codebase.\n162\t- Absolute first prompt of a new project (no convention to follow yet).\n163\t- Reproducing a published reference implementation that should match an external source line-for-line.\n164\t\n165\t#### Level 2 — Detailed (annotated skeleton)\n166\t\n167\t**Shape:** Function signatures and key error paths spelled out. Imports listed. Bodies left to the agent with hints (`// retry once on transient errors per DB#8`).\n168\t\n169\t**Pros:**\n170\t- Still very prescriptive about the contract surface.\n171\t- Manageable to audit (200–500 lines, not 1500).\n172\t- Less prone to style drift than Level 1 because bodies follow project conventions.\n173\t\n174\t**Cons:**\n175\t- The author still owns most of the logic; bugs in the spelled-out error paths still ship.\n176\t- The skeleton can subtly bias the agent away from a cleaner structure it would have chosen.\n177\t\n178\t**When to use:**\n179\t- Novel logic in a familiar project (the pattern doesn't exist yet, but the style does).\n180\t- Complex algorithms where the exact shape of the control flow matters.\n181\t- Migrating off a stable external API where the call sequence is fixed.\n182\t\n183\t#### Level 3 — Medium (contracts + references) — **default**\n184\t\n185\t**Shape:** Interface signatures, sequence of operations, pattern references (`see pkg/github/client.go for the errors.Wrapf style`), explicit failure modes copied from the spec, test scenarios named (`table-test the verdict × autoApprove matrix`). No function bodies. No pre-written error messages.\n186\t\n187\t**Pros:**\n188\t- Best for translation work — applying an existing project pattern to a new feature.\n189\t- Leverages the agent's pattern-matching strength: it reads the referenced file and adopts the style automatically.\n190\t- Small enough to audit at a contract level instead of a line-by-line review.\n191\t- Prompts age well — the contract changes rarely, the implementation can be regenerated.\n192\t- Author bugs in inlined code can't ship because there is no inlined code.\n193\t\n194\t**Cons:**\n195\t- Requires at least one good in-tree exemplar for each pattern referenced.\n196\t- Weaker models may produce non-uniform code across siblings without explicit shape.\n197\t- Reviewer must trust the contract rather than the implementation.\n198\t\n199\t**When to use:**\n200\t- Most refactors and feature work in mature codebases (the default).\n201\t- Multi-prompt specs where consistency across siblings matters.\n202\t- Any case where existing code already demonstrates the conventions the new code should follow.\n203\t\n204\t#### Level 4 — Soft (constraints + goals)\n205\t\n206\t**Shape:** What must be true at the end, plus references and constraints. No interfaces enumerated. Agent decides sequence, structure, and decomposition within the file.\n207\t\n208\t**Pros:**\n209\t- Maximum agent agency — it can refactor adjacent code if that produces a cleaner result.\n210\t- Very small prompts; fast to write.\n211\t- The agent may discover a better abstraction than the author would have specified.\n212\t\n213\t**Cons:**\n214\t- Outcomes more variable across runs and model versions.\n215\t- Relies on agent capability and self-discipline; weaker models drift.\n216\t- Harder to review (less to compare against).\n217\t- Multi-prompt coordination breaks down — siblings may make incompatible decisions.\n218\t\n219\t**When to use:**\n220\t- Greenfield work with a capable model.\n221\t- Rapid iteration when the right shape is uncertain.\n222\t- Cleanup tasks where the agent is expected to use judgment about how far to refactor.\n223\t\n224\t#### Level 5 — Very Rough (intent)\n225\t\n226\t**Shape:** One paragraph stating intent. A single verification command. No constraints, no references.\n227\t\n228\t**Pros:**\n229\t- Trivial to write — minutes from idea to attempt.\n230\t- Forces the agent to do the design thinking.\n231\t- Useful as a \"first draft\" that can be refined into Level 3.\n232\t\n233\t**Cons:**\n234\t- Highly variable output; often produces wrong abstractions on first try.\n235\t- Usually needs multiple rounds with edits — total wall time is often longer than starting at Level 3.\n236\t- Almost never satisfies the audit DoD on first pass.\n237\t- No reproducibility — same prompt twice produces different code.\n238\t\n239\t**When to use:**\n240\t- Spike / exploration where the answer isn't yet known.\n241\t- Throwaway scripts.\n242\t- Rapidly evolving requirements where any specification will be out of date by the time it's written.\n243\t\n244\t### Choosing a level\n245\t\n246\t**The Level 3 default assumes documented patterns actually exist in the codebase.** In a messy or greenfield codebase with no stable exemplars, Level 3 is dishonest — the prompt promises \"see X for the style\" but X doesn't exist, and the agent silently slides back into inlining. If patterns aren't there yet, Level 2 (spelled-out signatures, hinted bodies) is more honest until a pattern is proven, then promote to Level 3.\n247\t\n248\t**Step 0 — Discover existing patterns before writing.** Spend ~2 minutes running searches like:\n249\t\n250\t```bash\n251\t# Error-wrapping style in this project\n252\trg -l 'errors\\.Wrapf|fmt\\.Errorf' pkg/ internal/ | head\n253\t\n254\t# HTTP client construction\n255\trg -l 'http\\.Client|net/http' pkg/ | head\n256\t\n257\t# Counterfeiter mock pattern\n258\trg -l 'counterfeiter:generate' pkg/ | head\n259\t\n260\t# Test framework\n261\trg -l 'ginkgo\\.|gomega\\.|testing\\.T' pkg/ | head\n262\t```\n263\t\n264\tIf a surface returns 5+ matches with a consistent pattern → Level 3 references work. If it returns 0–2 → that pattern is novel for this codebase; choose Level 2 or document the new convention in a project doc first.\n265\t\n266\t**Then ask in order:**\n267\t\n268\t1. **Did Step 0 find ≥5 matches with a consistent pattern for the surface you're touching?**\n269\t   - Yes → continue to question 2.\n270\t   - No → **patterns are missing or inconsistent.** Continue to question 4 (do NOT silently fall through to Level 3 — that's the trap).\n271\t2. **Is this a published external API that must match line-for-line?**\n272\t   - Yes → Level 1 (and link the external source).\n273\t   - No → **Level 3** (reference the exemplars from Step 0; don't re-inline). This is the common case for translation work in mature codebases.\n274\t3. *(unreachable from question 1; kept for symmetry with prior versions)*\n275\t4. **(Patterns missing.) Will the agent need to invent a novel structure?**\n276\t   - Yes → Level 4 or 5 (let it explore), then promote to Level 3 once the pattern is proven AND document it in `project/docs/`.\n277\t   - No (translation work but no exemplar yet) → **Level 2** (spelled-out signatures, hinted bodies) — more honest than fake Level 3 references that don't exist. Promote to Level 3 in a future prompt once the pattern is documented.\n278\t\n279\t**The \"fall-through-to-Level-3\" trap:** the most common mistake. Author runs no searches, picks Level 3 because it's the \"default\", references files that don't exist or don't demonstrate the pattern claimed. Agent silently inlines (because it has nothing to reference), and the prompt produces author-style code anyway — back to the original problem. Step 0 + question 1's hard split prevents this.\n280\t\n281\t### What the spectrum does NOT solve\n282\t\n283\tPattern-anchoring (Level 3) solves **convention-drift bugs** — the agent adopts the project's existing style automatically. It does **not** solve **logic bugs in genuinely novel code**. Examples that no exemplar would catch:\n284\t\n285\t- `io.LimitReader(resp.Body, 500)` placed BEFORE `json.Unmarshal` — truncates the body before parsing, but no existing file demonstrates the right ordering because no existing file has this exact concern.\n286\t- A retry classifier that maps \"POST returned 200 but review absent in GET\" to the wrong error class — the logic itself is wrong, not the style.\n287\t- An off-by-one in pagination, an inverted boolean, a swapped argument order.\n288\t\n289\tThese need **test cases the agent must satisfy** (spec acceptance criteria, failure-modes table, scenario tests) or **adversarial review** — they cannot be prevented by referring to exemplars. The detail spectrum reduces *one class* of bug; the other class needs spec-level rigor.\n290\t\n291\t### Worked example: bot-identity self-check at three levels\n292\t\n293\tSame surface (verify the GitHub bot account matches `BOT_GITHUB_LOGIN` before posting), three grain levels:\n294\t\n295\t**Level 1 — Very Detailed**\n296\t\n297\t```text\n298\t## Step 4 — Implement BotIdentityCheck\n299\t\n300\tCreate function `func CheckBotIdentity(ctx context.Context, client HTTPClient, expectedLogin string) error`:\n301\t\n302\t1. Build request:\n303\t   req, err := http.NewRequestWithContext(ctx, \"GET\", \"https://api.github.com/user\", nil)\n304\t   if err != nil {\n305\t       return fmt.Errorf(\"build request: %w\", err)\n306\t   }\n307\t   req.Header.Set(\"Authorization\", \"token \"+token)\n308\t   req.Header.Set(\"Accept\", \"application/vnd.github+json\")\n309\t\n310\t2. Execute request:\n311\t   resp, err := client.Do(req)\n312\t   if err != nil {\n313\t       return fmt.Errorf(\"execute request: %w\", err)\n314\t   }\n315\t   defer resp.Body.Close()\n316\t\n317\t[... 60 more lines of fully-written Go ...]\n318\t```\n319\t\n320\t**Cost:** The author wrote `fmt.Errorf` from memory. The project uses `errors.Wrapf(ctx, err, ...)`. The agent will faithfully ship `fmt.Errorf` — every test passes; `make precommit` lint fails or worse, the convention drifts silently.\n321\t\n322\t**Level 3 — Medium (default)**\n323\t\n324\t```text\n325\t## Bot identity check (DB#4 in spec 027)\n326\t\n327\tContract:\n328\t- Function: CheckBotIdentity(ctx, client HTTPClient, expectedLogin string) error\n329\t- Returns nil iff GitHub's GET /user response's `login` field equals expectedLogin\n330\t- Returns errors.Wrapf(ctx, ErrBotIdentityMismatch, \"got %q, want %q\", actual, expectedLogin) on mismatch\n331\t- Returns wrapped error on HTTP / parse failure per the retry-policy classification\n332\t\n333\tPattern references (read before writing):\n334\t- `pkg/github/client.go` for HTTP+errors.Wrapf style and Authorization header construction\n335\t- `pkg/githubauth/types.go` for the HTTPClient interface shape and Counterfeiter annotation\n336\t- `pkg/verdict.go` for sentinel-error pattern (see `ErrUnknownVerdict`)\n337\t\n338\tTest (use DescribeTable):\n339\t- happy: 200 + login=expectedLogin → nil\n340\t- mismatch: 200 + login=other → wrapped ErrBotIdentityMismatch\n341\t- transient: network error → wrapped per pkg/github/client.go classification\n342\t- malformed: non-JSON response → wrapped, treated as permanent\n343\t```\n344\t\n345\t**Cost:** None of the inlined bugs are possible — the agent reads `pkg/github/client.go` and adopts the existing `errors.Wrapf` style, header construction, and error classification. ~25 lines of prompt vs ~70.\n346\t\n347\t**Level 5 — Very Rough**\n348\t\n349\t```text\n350\t## Bot identity check\n351\t\n352\tThe agent self-checks that the GitHub PAT belongs to `my-bot-account`\n353\tbefore posting any review. Mismatch → refuse + diagnostic.\n354\t\n355\tverification: make precommit\n356\t```\n357\t\n358\t**Cost:** The agent might invent the function in the wrong package, miss the retry-policy integration, or choose a different error sentinel. Works for spike/exploration; needs rewrite for production.\n359\t\n360\tWhen in doubt, write **Level 3** and let audit suggest tightening to Level 2 if the agent would be likely to drift.\n361\t\n362\t### State the why, not just the what\n363\t\n364\t`<objective>` should answer *why this change matters* in one clause, not just what to build. Models reason better when they know the purpose — same effort, fewer wrong abstractions.\n365\t\n366\t```\n367\tBAD:  Add a validation command field to project config.\n368\tGOOD: Add a validation command field to project config so projects can enforce repo-specific checks (e.g. `make precommit`) before a prompt is marked complete.\n369\t```\n370\t\n371\tThe \"why\" also constrains the agent: if it considers a shortcut that breaks the stated purpose, it has a reason to reject it.\n372\t\n373\t### Anchor by name, not line number\n374\t\n375\tLine numbers go stale when prior prompts edit the same file:\n376\t\n377\t```\n378\tBAD:  \"At line 231, wrap the error\"\n379\tGOOD: \"In ProcessQueue, after the autoSetQueuedStatus call, wrap the error\"\n380\t```\n381\t\n382\t### Copy constraints from spec\n383\t\n384\tThe agent has no memory between prompts. Every prompt must repeat the relevant constraints from the spec.\n385\t\n386\t### One concern per prompt\n387\t\n388\tSmaller prompts succeed more often. Group coupled behaviors together, but don't mix unrelated changes.\n389\t\n390\t### Repo-relative paths only\n391\t\n392\tDark-factory runs prompts in a Docker container. Never use absolute paths (`/Users/...`) or home-relative paths (`~/...`).\n393\t\n394\t**Exception**: Files under the mounted claude config use the in-container path `/home/node/.claude/plugins/...`, NOT the host path `~/.claude-yolo/plugins/...`. See [yolo-container-setup.md](../yolo-container-setup.md#project-workspace-mount).\n395\t\n396\t### Cross-repo references\n397\t\n398\tIf a prompt needs to reference code in a sibling repo (e.g., a library at `~/Documents/workspaces/time/`), the file is NOT accessible inside the container. Options:\n399\t\n400\t1. **Point to the vendored copy** — `vendor/github.com/bborbe/time/time_parse-time.go` (preferred when the dep is already vendored).\n401\t2. **Add an `extraMount`** in `.dark-factory.yaml` to mount the sibling repo.\n402\t3. **Inline the relevant snippet** in the prompt body.\n403\t\n404\tNever leave a host-absolute path hoping the agent will figure it out — the agent will get a \"file not found\" and fail.\n405\t\n406\t### Test the boundaries the new code crosses\n407\t\n408\tA broad class of bug: new code passes every unit test because the tests verify the **shape** of what was added, but fails at runtime because it crosses a **boundary** (library validator, parser, dispatch registry, serialization, subprocess, external service) and that boundary imposes a constraint the shape tests never exercise.\n409\t\n410\t**Rule:** For every boundary the new code crosses, at least one test must traverse that boundary with the new value. Ask: *what happens to this value after it leaves the code I just wrote?*\n411\t\n412\t**Root cause framing:** the problem is *missing integration tests* — tests that exercise the same code path production traffic takes. The \"validator test\" pattern below is a cheap, mechanically-enforceable subset.\n413\t\n414\t**Common boundaries and their contracts:**\n415\t\n416\t- **Library validators / parsers** — `Validate()`, `Parse()`, `Check()`, `MustX()` enforce regex / schema / range / format at runtime. The Go compiler does not check the underlying string.\n417\t- **Registries and dispatch tables** — adding a handler / operation / route is not enough; the dispatcher must find it via the production lookup path.\n418\t- **Serialization round-trips** — JSON / YAML / protobuf tags, nested types, zero-value handling. A round-trip test is the contract.\n419\t- **External service contracts** — Kafka operation names, Prometheus label regex, DNS labels, URL schemes, HTTP route patterns.\n420\t- **Subprocess interfaces** — argv, env vars, stdin/stdout shape, exit codes. A wrong flag name silently fails.\n421\t- **Build-time constraints** — build tags, `go:generate` directives, struct tags read by code generators.\n422\t\n423\t**Two acceptable levels:**\n424\t\n425\t1. **Unit-level contract test** (cheap; use this when a single-function validator/parser exists): call the boundary function directly on the new value — `Validate(ctx)`, `Parse(...)`, marshal+unmarshal. For grouped values of the same library type, a table test enumerating all values in the package is the canonical shape.\n426\t\n427\t   ```go\n428\t   // IMPORTANT: every new <TypeName> below MUST also appear in the Validate-all\n429\t   // test table in <matching_test.go>. The boundary contract is only enforced\n430\t   // at runtime — the test is the only pre-deploy guard.\n431\t   ```\n432\t\n433\t2. **Integration test through the real boundary** (more thorough; use this when no single-function validator exists, or when the change introduces a new integration seam — publish path, registry entry, new CLI flag): drive the new value through the real production path in a test harness.\n434\t\n435\t**Scope note:** E2E deployment verification (dev deploy + smoke tests) is a spec/scenario concern, not a prompt concern. Prompts cover unit and integration; specs cover acceptance; scenarios cover end-to-end.\n436\t\n437\t**What does NOT satisfy this rule:**\n438\t\n439\t- Struct equality tests (`Expect(cmd.TaskIdentifier).To(Equal(\"foo\"))`)\n440\t- Accessor-default tests (`Expect(fm.TriggerCount()).To(Equal(0))`)\n441\t- Constant-value tests (`Expect(string(OpX)).To(Equal(\"op-x\"))`) — these assert what you typed, not what the boundary accepts.\n442\t\n443\t**Why this rule exists:** in a real incident, `IncrementFrontmatterCommandOperation = \"increment_frontmatter\"` (underscores) passed every unit test but was rejected at runtime by the cqrs validator's regex `^[a-z][a-z-]*$`, causing a silent message-retry loop in dev that took a deploy cycle to diagnose. A six-line table test calling `.Validate(ctx)` on each declared operation would have caught it at `make precommit`.\n444\t\n445\t### Never run `go mod vendor` in a prompt\n446\t\n447\t`vendor/` is a build-time artifact: gitignored, regenerated by `make buca` before `docker build`. `make precommit`'s `ensure` target wipes it and uses `-mod=mod`. Dark-factory doesn't build Docker images, so nothing it does needs `vendor/`.\n448\t\n449\tDep bump: `go get foo@v1.2.3 && go mod tidy` — that's it.\n450\t\n451\tException: if the repo commits `vendor/`, document that deviation in the prompt.\n452\t\n453\t### Add imports before tidying\n454\t\n455\t`go mod tidy` (and `make ensure`, which calls it) removes any direct entry from `go.mod` that no code currently imports. A prompt step that does `go get foo@v1.2.3 && go mod tidy` BEFORE the file that imports `foo` is written will silently demote/remove the dep — the next `make precommit` then fails on the unresolved import.\n456\t\n457\t```\n458\tBAD:  Step 1: go get foo && go mod tidy\n459\t      Step 2: write code that imports foo\n460\t      → Step 1 left go.mod unchanged because nothing imported foo yet\n461\tGOOD: Step 1: write code that imports foo\n462\t      Step 2: go mod tidy (promotes foo to a direct dep)\n463\t```\n464\t\n465\tFor prompts that add a new dependency: state the order explicitly — write the import first, then tidy.\n466\t\n467\t### `make ensure` vs `make precommit` mid-implementation\n468\t\n469\tWhen a prompt says \"add a new dependency\" or \"regenerate vendored code\", the intermediate state cannot pass `make precommit` (test+check fail until the code is updated). Use `make ensure` for dependency-only preparation steps, then reserve `make precommit` for final verification.\n470\t\n471\t```\n472\tBAD: Step 1: \"Run `make precommit` to add the dep.\"   # fails — tests reference code not yet written\n473\tGOOD: Step 1: \"Run `make ensure` to add the dep.\"     # deps only\n474\t      Step N (last): \"Run `make precommit`.\"          # full check at the end\n475\t```\n476\t\n477\t## Decomposition\n478\t\n479\tWhen breaking a spec into multiple prompts:\n480\t\n481\t**The grouping test:** \"Can these behaviors be verified independently?\" If not, group them.\n482\t\n483\t**The verifiability test:** \"Can I write a test that distinguishes before vs after?\" If not, merge or sharpen.\n484\t\n485\t**Sequencing:** Most foundational prompt first. Each prompt's postconditions become the next prompt's preconditions.\n486\t\n487\t| Feature size | Typical prompts |\n488\t|--------------|----------------|\n489\t| Config change | 1 |\n490\t| Single feature | 2-3 |\n491\t| Major feature | 4-6 |\n492\t| Full project bootstrap | 8-15 |\n493\t\n494\t## Prompt Definition of Done\n495\t\n496\tA prompt is ready for approval when ALL checks pass:\n497\t\n498\t**Structure:**\n499\t- [ ] All sections present: `<summary>`, `<objective>`, `<context>`, `<requirements>`, `<constraints>`, `<verification>`\n500\t- [ ] `<summary>` has 5-10 plain-language bullets (no file paths or jargon)\n501\t- [ ] `<objective>` states end state in 1-3 sentences\n502\t- [ ] `<requirements>` are numbered, specific, unambiguous\n503\t- [ ] `<constraints>` copied from spec\n504\t- [ ] `<verification>` has a runnable command\n505\t\n506\t**Accuracy:**\n507\t- [ ] File paths exist and are correct\n508\t- [ ] Function names and signatures match current code\n509\t- [ ] No stale references to renamed/moved/deleted code\n510\t- [ ] All paths are repo-relative\n511\t\n512\t**Quality:**\n513\t- [ ] Independently verifiable\n514\t- [ ] Libraries specified with import paths\n515\t- [ ] No duplicates with completed prompts\n516\t- [ ] Every boundary the new code crosses (library validator, parser, registry, serialization, subprocess, external service) has a test that traverses it with the new value (see \"Test the boundaries the new code crosses\" above)\n517\t\n518\t## Audit and Approve\n519\t\n520\tAlways audit before approving:\n521\t\n522\t```\n523\t/dark-factory:audit-prompt prompts/my-change.md\n524\t```\n525\t\n526\tThen approve via CLI (never manually edit frontmatter):\n527\t\n528\t```bash\n529\tdark-factory prompt approve my-change\n530\t```\n531\t\n532\tThis moves the prompt from `prompts/` to `prompts/in-progress/`, assigns a number, and sets `status: queued`.\n533\t\n534\t**Direct workflow:** Can approve multiple prompts at once — they execute sequentially on the same branch.\n535\t\n536\t**PR workflow:** Approve one at a time — each depends on the previous being merged.\n537\t\n538\t## Prompt Status Lifecycle\n539\t\n540\t| Status | Directory | Meaning | How it happens |\n541\t|--------|-----------|---------|----------------|\n542\t| `idea` | `prompts/ideas/` | Rough concept, needs refinement | Human creates file |\n543\t| `draft` | `prompts/` | Complete, ready for review and approval | Human/AI creates file |\n544\t| `approved` | `prompts/in-progress/` | Queued for execution | `dark-factory prompt approve` |\n545\t| `executing` | `prompts/in-progress/` | YOLO container running | Auto (dark-factory) |\n546\t| `committing` | `prompts/in-progress/` | Container succeeded, git commit pending | Auto (dark-factory) |\n547\t| `completed` | `prompts/completed/` | Done, archived | Auto (dark-factory) |\n548\t| `failed` | `prompts/in-progress/` | Needs fix or retry | Auto (dark-factory) |\n549\t| `cancelled` | `prompts/in-progress/` | Pulled before/during execution | `dark-factory prompt cancel <id>` |\n550\t\n551\tCompleted prompts are immutable. If behavior changes later, create a new prompt.\n552\t\n553\t### Fixing an Approved Prompt\n554\t\n555\tTo edit a prompt that has already been approved (or is executing) without recreating it:\n556\t\n557\t```bash\n558\tdark-factory prompt cancel <id>     # sets status: cancelled\n559\t# edit the .md file to fix issues\n560\tdark-factory prompt requeue <id>    # sets status: queued, re-enters the execution queue\n561\t```\n562\t\n563\tNote: `unapprove` does NOT work on `cancelled` prompts (error: \"only approved prompts can be unapproved\"). Use `requeue`.\n564\t\n565\tNever manually edit the `status:` frontmatter — always use the CLI commands.\n566\t\n567\t## Next Steps\n568\t\n569\t- Run the pipeline: [running.md](../running.md)\n570\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"call_function_gndwq2feccxh_3","session_id":"213d66d0-dce3-49f1-a7b2-16c36173f959","uuid":"2b91b12b-9fb1-4e4c-aa52-2b62a37b6bd2","timestamp":"2026-06-27T21:34:06.596Z","subagent_type":"dark-factory:prompt-auditor","task_description":"Audit prompt 3"}
