{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_m1Szb5uggk56pnnCzVV9gr4E","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Spec Verification Guide\n2\t\n3\tWhen all prompts linked to a spec complete, dark-factory auto-transitions the spec to `verifying`. The spec sits in `specs/in-progress/` waiting for a human to confirm the acceptance criteria actually hold before it moves to `specs/completed/`.\n4\t\n5\tThis guide is the checklist for that confirmation step.\n6\t\n7\t## Use `/dark-factory:verify-spec` to operationalize this guide\n8\t\n9\tThe `/dark-factory:verify-spec <spec-id>` command invokes the `spec-verifier` agent, which walks Setup → Action → Expected interactively, applies the anti-evidence rejection rules from this guide as hard refusals, matches each Acceptance Criterion to fresh observable evidence, and only then runs `dark-factory spec complete <id>`. Prefer the command over a manual walk — it makes the rejection rules mechanical instead of vibes-based.\n10\t\n11\tManual walk (this guide's procedure below) is still the right move when:\n12\t- The spec has no scenario file and is purely structural (doc-only / refactor)\n13\t- You're auditing the verification approach itself\n14\t- The agent is unavailable\n15\t\n16\t## Why Verify\n17\t\n18\tPrompt completion means \"Claude said done and precommit passed on a per-prompt basis\". It does not mean:\n19\t\n20\t- All acceptance criteria checkboxes are actually true\n21\t- The cross-prompt behaviour composes correctly\n22\t- Docs and CHANGELOG were updated\n23\t- Dead code from earlier specs was removed (common when the new spec supersedes an older one)\n24\t- **The feature actually works when you run it** — green tests ≠ working feature\n25\t\n26\tVerification catches the gap between \"prompts ran\" and \"spec is satisfied\".\n27\t\n28\t## What to Verify — Three Layers\n29\t\n30\tEvery verification touches three dimensions. Skip one and the bug surfaces in production instead.\n31\t\n32\t| Layer | Verifies | Evidence | Cheapest to catch here because… |\n33\t|---|---|---|---|\n34\t| **Technical** | Code matches spec | file:line greps, unit tests, `make precommit` | Mechanical; compiler and tests do most of the work |\n35\t| **Business / feature** | Spec matches intent | Goal + Desired Behavior hold end-to-end; docs/CHANGELOG reflect user-visible change | Catches scope creep and non-goal violations before they ship |\n36\t| **Scenarios** | Reality matches spec | Each Failure Modes row reproducible or test-covered; manual smoke test on dev; Security/Abuse cases exercised | Integration bugs hide until real traffic hits them |\n37\t\n38\t**Rule of thumb:** technical asks \"did we build it right?\", business asks \"did we build the right thing?\", scenarios ask \"does it survive the real world?\". All three must pass.\n39\t\n40\tMap each acceptance criterion to the layer it belongs to:\n41\t\n42\t- \"Writer does not modify X\" → technical\n43\t- \"Operator-visible behaviour Y no longer happens\" → business\n44\t- \"Pod eviction during spawn does not inflate counter\" → scenario\n45\t\n46\tIf all your ACs cluster in one layer, the spec is probably underspecified — flag to the author.\n47\t\n48\t## When to Verify\n49\t\n50\t| Trigger | Action |\n51\t|---|---|\n52\t| `dark-factory status` shows spec in `verifying` | Start verification |\n53\t| Human review requested in daemon notification | Start verification |\n54\t| After a batch of related specs land | Verify each in order of approval |\n55\t\n56\tDo not verify while prompts are still queued or running — wait for auto-transition.\n57\t\n58\t**Verify in approval order, lowest spec number first.** Do not skip a spec to verify a later one. Specs typically build on each other (spec N+1 may depend on contracts asserted by spec N). If spec N reveals a defect that blocks completion, leave it in `verifying` and stack a fix prompt — do not jump ahead to N+1, because verifying N+1 against an unstable N produces ambiguous live evidence. Once N is clean, proceed sequentially.\n59\t\n60\t## Verification Procedure\n61\t\n62\tRun these six checks in order. Stop at the first failure.\n63\t\n64\t### 1. Read the Spec\n65\t\n66\tOpen `specs/in-progress/<id>-<name>.md`. Focus on three sections:\n67\t\n68\t- **Acceptance Criteria** — the binary checkboxes you must confirm\n69\t- **Verification** — the exact commands the spec author committed to\n70\t- **Constraints** — especially \"must not regress\" and \"must not change\"\n71\t\n72\tIf the spec supersedes another (look for \"supersedes\" in Summary), also open the superseded spec and confirm its load-bearing code is actually removed, not just bypassed.\n73\t\n74\t### 2. Confirm Code Matches Each Acceptance Criterion\n75\t\n76\tFor each checkbox, grep or read the file(s) it references. Prefer targeted grep over full-file reads.\n77\t\n78\t- Interface/behaviour criterion (e.g. \"writer does not modify X\") → grep the implementation, read ±20 lines\n79\t- Test criterion (e.g. \"unit test covers Y\") → grep the test file for the described case\n80\t- Doc criterion (e.g. \"CHANGELOG notes Z\") → grep the doc\n81\t- Removal criterion (e.g. \"guard from spec N is gone\") → grep should return no hits; if hits remain, verification fails\n82\t\n83\tRecord each criterion as confirmed or failed. Do not mark verified by vibes — cite file:line.\n84\t\n85\t### 3. Run the Spec's Verification Commands\n86\t\n87\tRun exactly what the spec's `## Verification` section lists. Do not substitute equivalents.\n88\t\n89\tTypical pattern for Go specs in this repo:\n90\t\n91\t```bash\n92\tcd <module> && go test ./...\n93\t# or\n94\tcd <module> && make precommit\n95\t```\n96\t\n97\tDelegate long-running commands to `simple-bash-runner` so the main context doesn't drown in output.\n98\t\n99\tIf the spec has a manual smoke test (e.g. on dev cluster), either:\n100\t\n101\t- Run it yourself and record the result, or\n102\t- Explicitly note that manual smoke is deferred and mark the spec `verified-minus-smoke` in the verification summary\n103\t\n104\t### 4. Find Live Evidence the Feature Actually Works\n105\t\n106\tTests passing ≠ feature works. Tests prove the code does what the author thought; they don't prove the deployed system does what the user needs. Before marking complete, look for evidence from a running system.\n107\t\n108\tPreferred sources, strongest first:\n109\t\n110\t- **Run it live.** Trigger the feature in dev/staging with a realistic input. Watch it happen.\n111\t- **Logs from an already-running instance.** If the feature has shipped to dev (via `make buca` or similar), pull logs and find the log lines that prove the new behaviour fired. Grep for the code path added by this spec.\n112\t- **Metrics / dashboards.** If the spec added counters or gauges, query them — non-zero values from a real run are strong evidence.\n113\t- **Git history of real task runs.** For dark-factory itself: check `.dark-factory.log`, prompt logs, or vault commit history for a run that exercised the new path.\n114\t- **Before/after comparison.** Same input, old version vs new version — the diff in behaviour is the evidence.\n115\t\n116\tWhat to record for each AC that needs live evidence:\n117\t\n118\t- The command or trigger you ran\n119\t- The log line, metric value, or output that proves it worked\n120\t- Timestamp + environment (dev/staging cluster, local, etc.)"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"call_function_gndwq2feccxh_3","session_id":"213d66d0-dce3-49f1-a7b2-16c36173f959","uuid":"dbc1d76c-ea1d-43fc-8946-a56952ecc94c","timestamp":"2026-06-27T21:34:09.564Z","subagent_type":"dark-factory:prompt-auditor","task_description":"Audit prompt 3"}
