e capture)\n- [N/A] Security concerns — spec's Security section says \"Not applicable\" (line 71 of spec)\n- [N/A] External calls — the prompt contains `kubectlquant` calls but explicitly states the operator runs them, not the YOLO container; timeout is not specified because the operator drives interactively\n- [x] No `go mod vendor` in `<requirements>` or `<verification>`\n- [x] No cross-repo writes (no `git clone` of external remote + write; the buca workflow is to the project's own repo + a same-day companion commit in `bborbe/quant` which is NOT touched by this prompt — line 142 explicitly says \"Do NOT touch the `bborbe/quant` repo from this prompt\")\n\n## Container-Autonomy — **CRITICAL FAILURE**\n\n- [FAIL] **Operator-only steps throughout.** Requirement 1 (Pre-conditions) instructs running `kubectlquant`, `git pull`, `git merge`, `BRANCH=dev make buca` — all forbidden inside the YOLO container per `~/.claude-yolo/CLAUDE.md` (\"no kubectl in containers\").\n- [FAIL] **Operator-only steps in AC4 probe procedure (requirement 2):** `cd ~/Documents/Obsidian/Personal`, `touch`, `git add`, `git commit`, `git push` to `obsidian-personal.git` (a vault remote the YOLO has no credentials for), `kubectlquant logs | grep`, cleanup `rm && git commit && git push`.\n- [FAIL] **Operator-only steps in AC5 probe procedure (requirement 4):** identical host-path manipulation + `kubectlquant` + `git log` on the vault.\n- [FAIL] **Cross-repo write to vault remote.** The YOLO container has no credentials for `obsidian-personal.git`. Steps `git push origin master` from `~/Documents/Obsidian/Personal` to that remote will fail at runtime and the local commit is unrecoverable when the container exits.\n- [FAIL] **The prompt itself acknowledges this.** Line 28: \"the probe cannot run from this YOLO container.\" Line 30: \"This prompt assumes the operator (NOT the YOLO container) executes it.\" The prompt admits it is the wrong artifact type and then ships anyway.\n- [FAIL] **Spec verification ladder is the correct location.** Per `/home/node/.claude/plugins/marketplaces/dark-factory/docs/spec-verification.md` (lines 7–9, 88–104), post-deploy ACs belong to the spec's `## Verification` section and are operationalized by `/dark-factory:verify-spec <spec-id>`, which is operator-driven (or `simple-bash-runner` delegated). The spec's own `## Verification` section at lines 105–115 of `001-scanner-auto-inject-flag.md` ALREADY contains the post-merge commands for both rungs.\n- [FAIL] **Operator-vs-agent split inside the prompt.** The split is implicit throughout (requirements are written for the operator; the container is told \"this is not for you\"). This is the explicit tell that the artifact is the wrong type. From the framework's container-autonomy rule: \"An 'operator note', 'hand this to the operator', or an Operator-vs-Agent step split inside the prompt — that split is the tell that the artifact is the wrong type. Splitting steps does NOT fix it; the operator half does not belong in a prompt at all.\"\n\n## Sibling-Coverage Check\n\n- [x] Sibling prompts 1 and 2 cover AC1/AC6, AC2/AC3/AC7 respectively. This prompt covers AC4/AC5. Sibling decomposition is clean.\n- [N/A] No edit to setup/gate/validation function — this prompt does not modify code, so the sibling-grep rule does not apply.\n\n## Documentation Placement\n\n- [x] No inlined reusable patterns to extract\n- [x] No project docs ignored — `<context>` correctly points to the spec AC4/AC5 sections and the git-workflow.md\n- [N/A] No coding plugin docs relevant (no Go code patterns here)\n\n## Code Reference Verification\n\n| Reference | File | Status |\n|-----------|------|--------|\n| `pkg/scanner/vault_scanner.go` lines 261/264/268 (trigger sites) | `/workspace/pkg/scanner/vault_scanner.go` | Verified — `taskID == \"\"` at 261, `isValidUUID` at 264, `isIdentifierUnique` at 268 |\n| Spec line references (\"lines 240–256\", \"lines 261/264/268\", \"line 275\") | spec context only, not used in this prompt | Verified via grep on the scanner file |\n| `/home/node/.claude/plugins/marketplaces/coding/docs/git-workflow.md` | exists, relevant | Verified |\n| `~/Documents/Obsidian/Personal` (vault worktree) | Not in container | NOT a code reference — but a host path the container cannot resolve |\n| `~/Documents/workspaces/agent-dev`, `~/Documents/workspaces/agent-prod` | Not in container | NOT a code reference — but a host path |\n| `obsidian-personal.git` (vault remote) | Not accessible | NOT a code reference — but the YOLO has no git credentials |\n| `kubectlquant` | operator-only CLI | Not in container |\n\nThe only code references in the prompt (the scanner line numbers) verify correctly. The non-code references are the actual problem — they target host-only paths and operator-only tooling.\n\n## Coding Guidelines Compliance\n\n- [N/A] No Go code in `<requirements>` to violate guidelines.\n\n## YAGNI Pass (scope-creep detector)\n\n- [N/A] This prompt does not ship code or config knobs; no YAGNI surface.\n- [Note] The prompt scope-creeps in the OPPOSITE direction — it ships the operator's full runbook (AC4 + AC5 step-by-step) into a container artifact that should not exist. The spec already carries this content in its `## Verification` section.\n\n## Critical Issues\n\n**1. Container-autonomy violation (CRITICAL — framework's most severe failure mode).** Requirement 1 (Pre-conditions), Requirement 2 (AC4 probe), Requirement 3 (AC5 pre-conditions), and Requirement 4 (AC5 probe) all instruct `kubectlquant`, `BRANCH=dev/prod make buca`, and `git push` against `obsidian-personal.git` — operations the YOLO container cannot perform (no cluster credentials, no vault remote credentials, no `kubectlquant` binary). The prompt's own `<context>` (line 28) acknowledges \"the probe cannot run from this YOLO container.\" This is the framework's highest-severity failure mode because the work is irrecoverable: any local commits inside the container are lost when it exits.\n\n**Suggested fix wording:** Container-autonomy violation. Requirements 1, 2, 3, and 4 instruct `kubectlquant describe deploy/pod`, `kubectlquant logs | grep`, `BRANCH={dev|prod} make buca`, and `git push origin master` to `obsidian-personal.git` from `~/Documents/Obsidian/Personal` — all operator-only operations the read-only dark-factory container cannot execute (no cluster creds, no vault remote credentials, no `kubectlquant` binary). The prompt explicitly acknowledges this in `<context>` and is therefore the wrong artifact type. **Fix:** delete this prompt. The spec's `## Verification` section (lines 96–116 of `001-scanner-auto-inject-flag.md`) already contains the exact post-merge procedure for AC4 and AC5. When all three prompts complete and the spec transitions to `verifying`, the operator runs `/dark-factory:verify-spec 001` which walks the AC4/AC5 evidence capture interactively per `docs/spec-verification.md`. There is no third artifact needed between the prompts and the spec verification ladder.\n\n**2. Cross-repo write to vault remote (CRITICAL).** Requirement 2 step 1 (`git push origin master` from `~/Documents/Obsidian/Personal`) and Requirement 4 step 1 (same) push to `obsidian-personal.git` — a remote the YOLO container has no credentials for. Per the framework's cross-repo-write rule, the in-container push will fail, the daemon will mark the prompt failed, and the local probe commit inside the container is unrecoverable.\n\n**Suggested fix wording:** Cross-repo write detected. Requirements 2 and 4 push to `obsidian-personal.git` from `~/Documents/Obsidian/Personal` — a vault remote the dark-factory container has no credentials for. **Fix:** same as Issue 1 — move this work out of the prompt entirely.\n\n**3. Host-absolute / home-relative paths (CRITICAL).** Requirements contain `~/Documents/Obsidian/Personal`, `~/Documents/workspaces/agent-dev`, `~/Documents/workspaces/agent-prod`, and `~/Documents/workspaces/agent-dev/task/controller`. None of these resolve inside the container. (Note: `/workspace/specs/in-progress/001-scanner-auto-inject-flag.md` in `<context>` line 26 IS a valid in-container path — the workspace mount. The host-path violations are the `~/...` ones.)\n\n**Suggested fix wording:** Same as Issue 1. Removing the prompt fixes all path-portability violations.\n\n## Recommendations\n\n**1. Documentation placement.** The probe procedure's content is already preserved in the spec's `## Verification` section (lines 96–116). Duplicating it into a third artifact (a prompt) creates drift risk — if the spec verification procedure changes, the prompt also has to change. The spec is the single source of truth.\n\n**2. Filename semantics.** If the prompt were kept, the filename `003-spec-001-post-deploy-verification.md` is fine but the contents should be a runnable artifact, not a runbook. The current contents are 90% runbook, 10% placeholder (\"No code changes from this prompt\" — requirement 6).\n\n**3. Companion-commit dependency is under-specified in the prompt.** Line 13 mentions the `bborbe/quant` companion commit as a prerequisite for AC5 but doesn't pin which env vars it sets, which file it modifies, or how to verify it has landed. If the prompt were kept (against recommendation), this dependency would need to be a first-class requirement with a check (e.g., `kubectlquant -n prod get deploy agent-task-controller -o jsonpath='{.spec.template.spec.containers[0].env}' | grep AUTO_INJECT_TASK_IDENTIFIER`).\n\n**4. Evidence capture order is load-bearing but not failure-loud.** Requirement 2 and Requirement 4 both say \"capture evidence BEFORE cleanup\" — correct, but if the probe races (cleanup happens during a poll), the captured log line might be from a DIFFERENT poll cycle than the probe file. The prompt does not assert that the captured log line references the exact `relPath` of the probe file — AC4's evidence requirement (line 78 of spec) DOES assert this, but the prompt's wording \"≥1 matching line referencing the probe file's `relPath`\" is correct only if the grep pattern includes the full `relPath` (it does: `_test-probe-` prefix is matched). OK on this point, but if the prompt were kept this would benefit from being more explicit.\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The `<summary>` bullets are plain language and accurately describe the operator-driven nature of the work.\n- The author correctly identifies the `bborbe/quant` companion-commit dependency and surfaces it explicitly in `<constraints>` and `<summary>`.\n- Requirement 6 (\"No code changes from this prompt\") and Requirement 7 (\"No scenario file is generated\") show clear awareness of the spec's boundaries and the dark-factory workflow.\n- The `<context>` correctly references the spec's AC4 and AC5 sections rather than re-stating them.\n- Code references that ARE made (scanner line numbers for spec verification cross-checks) are accurate.\n- The \"Scope: verification only\" framing in requirement 6 is a deliberate, well-reasoned design choice — the author recognized that the post-deploy evidence belongs somewhere, and chose \"prompt\" as the location. The error is in the location, not the reasoning.\n\n## Summary\n\n**Critical structural failure: the artifact type is wrong.** This prompt is a complete, well-written operator runbook for the post-deploy verification rungs (AC4/AC5), but the dark-factory container cannot execute it — the container has no cluster credentials, no vault remote credentials, no `kubectlquant` binary, and no access to `~/Documents/Obsidian/Personal`. The prompt's own `<context>` admits this. The spec's `## Verification` section already contains the same procedure; the spec's auto-transition to `verifying` after all prompts complete will surface the runbook to the operator via `/dark-factory:verify-spec 001`. **Priority action: delete this prompt.** The spec verification ladder is the correct home for AC4/AC5 evidence capture. There is no third artifact needed.\n\nIf for some reason th