liant. |  |  |\n\n## YAGNI Pass (scope-creep detector)\n- [x] No opt-out flag introduced (no `disableAutoInject bool` etc.)\n- [x] Every step maps to a spec AC: step 1 → AC1 wiring, step 2 → AC1 behavior, step 3 → DB2 (factory plumbing), step 4 → DB2 + DB3 (private field), step 5 → mock sync, step 6 → DB2 wire-up, step 7 → AC1 reflection test, step 8 → AC1 behavioral test, step 9/10 → non-goals enforcement.\n- [x] No \"future-proofing\" knobs: spec Non-goal #1 explicitly forbids a default value, and the prompt enforces that.\n\n## Test Coverage\n- [x] Step 7: reflection test pins field shape (`TestApplicationAutoInjectTaskIdentifierFieldExists`).\n- [x] Step 8: Ginkgo behavioral test calls `argument.Parse(ctx, &app)` with `AUTO_INJECT_TASK_IDENTIFIER` unset and asserts an error containing the env name. **This is exactly the right boundary-crossing test** — it exercises the `argument` library's `ValidateRequired` end-to-end on the new field. Level-1 contract test satisfied.\n- [x] AC2/AC3/AC7 (gate logic tests) are explicitly deferred to prompt 2 — the spec's decomposition table accepts this.\n- [x] Test file placement is correct: `main_internal_test.go` for reflection (existing file, appended), `main_test.go` for behavioral Ginkgo (existing file, appended).\n\n## Critical Issues\n\n1. **Inline design evolution leaks into requirements (Step 3, lines 82–127)** — The prompt contains two abandoned design iterations (\"Pick option (b)...But this returns a `VaultScanner` interface...Revised correct shape: The factory does the wiring by calling `NewGitRestVaultScanner` and then exposing a setter.\"). This violates the implementation discipline rule \"Single decision per prompt — no rambling alternatives.\" A YOLO agent will spend cycles parsing the rejected branches. The final shape is correct but buried under draft noise.\n   **Fix**: Collapse Step 3 to one paragraph stating the chosen design (constructor + `SetAutoInject` setter), reference `vault_scanner.go:30` counterfeiter directive, and remove the 3 dead-end paragraphs.\n\n2. **Setter exposed publicly rather than via package-private mechanism** — Step 3 adds `SetAutoInject(enabled bool)` to the EXPORTED `VaultScanner` interface (line 108 of the prompt). This makes the gate bypassable by any future caller of the interface. The rejected options (a) and (b) were actually safer: package-private `WithAutoInject` on `*vaultScanner` (a), or a private constructor in `pkg/scanner/` called via the factory (b). Choosing (b) would have required the factory to import `pkg/scanner` (it already does) and would keep `SetAutoInject` off the public surface. **This is a security/correctness smell**, though not strictly an AC violation. The spec says \"surfacing on the scanner as a private boolean field\" — private field is correct, but a public setter on the interface is NOT what \"private\" means.\n   **Fix**: Either (i) keep `SetAutoInject` only on the concrete `*vaultScanner` (not the interface), and have the factory type-assert: `vs.(*vaultScanner).SetAutoInject(autoInject)`, or (ii) expose `SetAutoInject` only on the factory-side, with a clear comment that it's an init-time setter, not a runtime toggle. Option (ii) is what the prompt picks but it leaks onto the public interface.\n\n3. **Test in step 8 does not pin the spec's exact AC1 evidence wording** — Spec AC1 says: \"the returned error is non-nil ... envconfig required-field error string containing `AUTO_INJECT_TASK_IDENTIFIER`\". The prompt's step 8 says \"assert the error message contains the substring `AUTO_INJECT_TASK_IDENTIFIER`\" — that matches. However, the actual error message from `argument.ValidateRequired` is `\"Required field empty, define parameter auto-inject-task-identifier or define env AUTO_INJECT_TASK_IDENTIFIER\"`. The test would pass, but step 8 doesn't tell the agent to verify the literal format matches AC1's evidence requirement.\n   **Fix**: Add to step 8: assert the error message contains both the parameter name (`auto-inject-task-identifier`) and the env name (`AUTO_INJECT_TASK_IDENTIFIER`) — both substrings are produced by the library.\n\n## Recommendations\n\n1. **funlen risk in `Run()` (line 67 of `main.go`)** — `Run()` is currently 92 lines (already has a `//nolint:funlen`). Step 2 adds ~10 lines for `strconv.ParseBool` + error check, pushing it further. `funlen` allows 80 lines / 50 statements. The prompt should either extract the parse step into a helper (`a.parseAutoInject()`) or pre-emptively annotate with another `//nolint:funlen` comment explaining the +10 lines.\n\n2. **Counterfeiter regeneration step lacks a verification guard** — Step 5 says run `go generate ./pkg/scanner/...` and verify the mock has `SetAutoInject`. But `Makefile.precommit` runs `generate` which wipes `mocks/` first. If the agent runs only step 5 standalone, it might miss pre-initialization of the mock. The step is correct as written; just call out that the project's `make precommit` does the regeneration as part of its `generate` target, so step 5 can be skipped if the agent runs full precommit.\n\n3. **Step 8 says `argument.Parse(ctx, &app)` directly** — but `service.Main` (called in `main()` at line 45) wraps the parsing. The test calling `argument.Parse` directly is fine (it's a unit test, not running `main()`), but the prompt could be more explicit that this is an intentional choice to bypass `service.Main`.\n\n4. **Sister prompt 3 is operator-driven (kubectlquant, vault worktree writes)** — that's correct (out of scope for the YOLO container), but the prompt body should mention \"this prompt is code-only; prompts 2 and 3 cover gate logic and post-deploy verification respectively\" somewhere so the agent doesn't try to also wire up the gate logic in this prompt. Step 9 does this implicitly but could be more explicit.\n\n5. **Filename ordering prefix `001-`** — The pattern `^[1-9]-spec-\\d{3}-` allows single-digit ordering prefix. The prompt uses `001-spec-001-...` which has TWO `001-` segments. This is confusing: the filename has `001-spec-001-config-and-factory-wiring.md` where the first `001` is the prompt's order-in-batch and the second `001` is the spec number. The sibling `002-spec-001-scanner-gate-and-tests.md` and `003-spec-001-post-deploy-verification.md` follow the same convention. This is internally consistent and matches the documented pattern, but a reader might mis-parse it. **Acceptable** — no fix needed.\n\n## Strengths\n- The 3-prompt decomposition (config+factory → gate+tests → post-deploy) is exactly what the spec's \"Suggested Decomposition\" table prescribes. Prompt 1's scope is correctly bounded.\n- The library-boundary awareness is excellent: the prompt author verified `argument/v2` and discovered that `required:\"true\"` on `bool` is silently bypassed, then designed around it with `string` + explicit `strconv.ParseBool`. This is exactly the kind of failure mode the audit framework wants prompts to catch.\n- Step 7's reflection test is a smart regression guard against someone changing the field type back to `bool`.\n- Step 4's \"default `true` is critical — it preserves today's behavior for all existing test fixtures\" correctly identifies the sibling-caller parity concern.\n- The frozen-log-substring non-goal is correctly delegated to prompt 2 (it's noted but not required in prompt 1).\n- AC6's `make precommit` exit-code-0 verification is correctly placed in `<verification>`.\n\n## Summary\n\nThe prompt has a strong technical baseline — code references are all verified accurate, the library-boundary gotcha (bool `required:\"true\"`) is correctly identified and designed around, and the spec's 3-prompt decomposition is honored. Two issues should be fixed before approval:\n\n1. **Collapse the inline design evolution in Step 3** — remove the two rejected branches so the agent doesn't second-guess the chosen shape.\n2. **Reconsider the public `SetAutoInject` on the `VaultScanner` interface** — a public setter on the interface undermines the \"private boolean field\" language in the spec and lets future callers bypass the gate. Either keep it package-private or type-assert in the factory.\n\nThe third issue (test substring) is a minor tightening. The recommendations are polish items that can ship as-is. Verdict: **ship with the 2 critical cleanups above**.\n\n---\n\nWant me to:\n1. **Implement fixes** — apply the two critical cleanups and the funlen nit\n2. **Verify references** — deep-dive into the `SetAutoInject` interface-export decision (check if any other prompt or external code expects a specific interface shape)\n3. **Focus on critical only** — apply just the inline-design-evolution removal and the `SetAutoInject` privacy re-design"},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: ab46b9c041c36a0f4 (use SendMessage with to: 'ab46b9c041c36a0f4' to continue this agent)\n<usage>subagent_tokens: 57870\ntool_uses: 58\nduration_ms: 136486</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"213d66d0-dce3-49f1-a7b2-16c36173f959","uuid":"5149d8de-5e6f-451a-8aa5-e3bc87b1c782","timestamp":"2026-06-27T21:35:39.139Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Audit the dark-factory prompt file at `/workspace/prompts/001-spec-001-config-and-factory-wiring.md` against the Prompt Definition of Done.\n\nRead the prompt file fully, then read the spec file at `/workspace/Users/bborbe/Documents/workspaces/agent-task-controller-scanner-flag/specs/in-progress/001-scanner-auto-inject-flag.md` for context.\n\nRun all the checks described in the audit framework: verify every cited external symbol (grep the module source), verify every referenced file exists, check that all spec ACs are covered, check that the prompt has proper stub/fail-loud behavior, check naming conventions, etc.\n\nReturn the full audit report with PASS/FAIL/WARNING for each check category and a summary verdict.","agentId":"ab46b9c041c36a0f4","agentType":"dark-factory:prompt-auditor","content":[{"type":"text","text":"**CRITICAL ISSUE DETECTED**: T