q 11): \"It was already regenerated by prompt 1 (which added `SetAutoInject`)\"\n- Step 6 (`&vaultScanner{...}` literal search): assumes prompt 1's `autoInject` field exists, so zero-value `false` breaks existing tests\n\n**Fix:** Either (a) gate this prompt behind prompt 1 completion (add a `<prerequisites>` or sibling-coverage block making the dependency explicit), or (b) merge prompt 2 into prompt 1 so the field + gate ship together. Currently the prompt instructs the agent to compile against a field that does not exist.\n\n### C2. `glog.SetOutput` / `LogToStderr` API does not exist (BLOCKER)\nStep 9 of `<requirements>` asks the agent to choose between `glog.SetOutput`, `glog.LogToStderr`, or `klog.SetLogger` for capturing log output. Verified in `/home/node/go/pkg/mod/github.com/golang/glog@v1.2.5/`:\n\n- No `func SetOutput`\n- No `func LogToStderr`\n- No exported `func SetLogger`\n- The installed version uses `logsink.TextSinks` (unexported global slice, only mutable from inside the package)\n\nThe \"fallback\" suggestion (`flag.Set(\"logtostderr\", \"true\")` + parse stderr) is fragile and would not give clean access to the substring. AC3's evidence claim (\"glog capture matched with `ContainSubstring`\") cannot be satisfied with the installed glog version.\n\n**Fix:** Drop the glog-substring assertion. The counter increment assertion alone is sufficient evidence (helper is a single unit: log + counter). The spec's AC4 evidence is the operator-side `kubectl logs | grep`, not a unit test — there is no requirement to capture glog in unit tests.\n\n### C3. Parity-check arithmetic is wrong (TEST WILL FAIL)\nStep 5 claims the `skipCount` and `counterCount` go from 6 to 9. The implementation extracts `skipAutoInjectDisabled` as a separate helper method (per step 2's design choice). The parity-check test's awk regex captures only `processFile` AND `injectAndStore` function bodies (lines 1043-1044 of the existing test). Since the helper is a third function body, **its `glog.Warningf(\"skipping` and `SkippedFilesTotal(` occurrences are NOT counted**. The counts stay at 6 / 6.\n\nVerified empirically:\n```\n$ awk '/^func \\(v \\*vaultScanner\\) (processFile|injectAndStore)\\(/,/^}/' vault_scanner.go | grep -c 'glog.Warningf(\"skipping\\|glog.Errorf(\"skipping\\|glog.Warningf(\"failed to read'\n6\n$ awk '/^func \\(v \\*vaultScanner\\) (processFile|injectAndStore)\\(/,/^}/' vault_scanner.go | grep -c 'SkippedFilesTotal('\n6\n```\n\nAfter implementing the prompt's own design (helper extraction), the count remains 6 / 6. Updating the assertion to `9` will fail.\n\n**Fix:** Either (a) keep `Expect(skipCount).To(Equal(6))` and `Expect(counterCount).To(Equal(6))` (the parity invariant still holds because the helper is a single source location for the warn+counter pair, OR (b) update the awk regex to also include `skipAutoInjectDisabled`'s body so it counts the 3 calls and 3 log lines from inside the helper. Choose (b) and the new count is correct; choose (a) and leave the assertion unchanged. The current prompt's instruction to change 6 → 9 is incorrect under the current extraction design.\n\n### C4. `&vaultScanner{...}` literal at `vault_scanner_test.go` line 39 does not exist\nThe prompt's step 6 references \"every existing `&vaultScanner{...}` literal in `vault_scanner_test.go` (external test package, line 39)\" — but grep confirms no such literal exists in that file. `vault_scanner_test.go` uses the public `scanner.NewVaultScanner(...)` constructor (line 185, 502, 511, 531, 547, 947). Only `vault_scanner_internal_test.go:39` has the one literal.\n\n**Fix:** Correct the search target. The existing tests using `NewVaultScanner` will get `autoInject=true` automatically once prompt 1 initializes it to `true` in both constructors (per prompt 1 step 4). Only the one literal at `vault_scanner_internal_test.go:39` needs `autoInject: true` added.\n\n## Recommendations\n\n### R1. Inline pattern collision risk (Documentation)\nStep 9 inlines ~6 lines of \"which glog API to use\" branching. The coding plugin has `/home/node/.claude/plugins/marketplaces/coding/docs/go-glog-guide.md` that documents log capture patterns. Reference that doc in `<context>` and remove the inline branching, OR (better) drop the glog capture requirement entirely per C2.\n\n### R2. `Describe(\"autoInject flag\")` placement\nThe new `Describe(\"autoInject flag\", ...)` block is added to `vault_scanner_internal_test.go`. The existing file already has a `Describe(\"injectAndStore\", ...)` block at line 17. Consider grouping by concern: the `autoInject` flag is a property of `processFile`, not `injectAndStore`. Placing the new `Describe` next to the existing structure is fine but a short comment explaining the grouping helps future readers.\n\n### R3. `SkipCount` assertion comment is over-engineered\nStep 5's \"expected 9 skip-site log lines (3 existing + 1 write-failed + 1 read-failed + 1 empty-status + 3 auto-inject-disabled sites...\" arithmetic does not match the actual regex match count. After C3's fix, the comment should reflect the simpler truth: \"expected 6 skip-site log lines + 3 helper log lines + 3 helper counter calls\" or whatever the chosen invariant is.\n\n### R4. Test coverage gate missing\n`<requirements>` does not require `go test -coverprofile` verification for the new helper. Per the definition-of-done, new code (the `skipAutoInjectDisabled` helper) needs ≥80% statement coverage. Add a coverage check to `<verification>` or a `<constraints>` line.\n\n### R5. Helper signature — `*lib.Task` return unneeded\nThe proposed helper `skipAutoInjectDisabled(relPath string) (*lib.Task, string, bool)` returns three values matching the skip shape. That's fine, but the three trigger sites only need the boolean skip signal; they currently `return v.skipAutoInjectDisabled(relPath)` and the function signature is consistent. Acceptable.\n\n### R6. `<verification>` does not include the prompt's own new tests\nThe verification commands run `go test ./pkg/scanner/... -run TestSuite -v` which will pick up the new Ginkgo `It` blocks. The expected test names section correctly enumerates them. Good.\n\n### R7. Inline `fmt.Errorf` risk in future helper changes\nStep 2's helper does not use `fmt.Errorf`, but step 9's glog capture attempt may cause the agent to write test code with `fmt.Errorf`. Add a `<constraint>` reinforcing \"never `fmt.Errorf`\" for any new error returns.\n\n### R8. `init()` slice update is fragile\nStep 1 says add `ReasonAutoInjectDisabled` to the `init()` loop slice (lines 201-208). The slice literal is inline — adding an entry is safe. Verify the resulting Prometheus label name matches `ReasonAutoInjectDisabled` exactly (Prometheus enforces `[a-zA-Z_][a-zA-Z0-9_]*` on label values, \"auto_inject_disabled\" passes).\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The summary is well-written and human-reviewer-friendly\n- Frozen substring is preserved verbatim\n- Spec constraints are correctly referenced (Constraints #51, #53, #54)\n- The `writeCounterReset` exclusion is explicit and correct\n- Step 3 + 4 (\"Do NOT touch\") protect against scope creep\n- The AC coverage mapping is clear (AC2 → step 7, AC3 → step 8, AC7 → step 10)\n- Error wrapping convention is correctly cited (`errors.Errorf`, not `fmt.Errorf`)\n- Test framework choice (internal test package for unexported field access) is correct\n\n## Summary\n\nThe prompt is well-structured and reads cleanly, but it has three blockers that prevent execution: (1) prompt 1 has not merged, so the field it gates on does not exist; (2) the glog capture step (step 9) references API symbols that do not exist in the installed glog v1.2.5; (3) the parity-check arithmetic in step 5 is wrong (counts stay at 6/6, not 9/9) under the prompt's own helper-extraction design. Priority action: resolve the prompt-1 dependency first (either merge prompt 1 first or roll prompt 1's wiring into this prompt), then drop the glog capture requirement and fix the parity-check count expectation.\n\n---\n\n**Next steps — pick one:**\n1. **Implement fixes** — apply C1, C2, C3, C4 critical fixes\n2. **Verify references** — deep-dive into the `autoInject` dependency and parity-check arithmetic\n3. **Focus on critical only** — fix only C1 (prompt 1 dependency) since C2, C3, C4 are downstream of whether the prompt runs at all"},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a43d9eaae6111237e (use SendMessage with to: 'a43d9eaae6111237e' to continue this agent)\n<usage>subagent_tokens: 63898\ntool_uses: 82\nduration_ms: 174031</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"213d66d0-dce3-49f1-a7b2-16c36173f959","uuid":"318e3468-bc1d-420d-92d4-51ffbaa37394","timestamp":"2026-06-27T21:36:19.093Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Audit the dark-factory prompt file at `/workspace/prompts/002-spec-001-scanner-gate-and-tests.md` against the Prompt Definition of Done.\n\nRead the prompt file fully, then read the spec file at `/workspace/Users/bborbe/Documents/workspaces/agent-task-controller-scanner-flag/specs/in-progress/001-scanner-auto-inject-flag.md` for context.\n\nRun all the checks described in the audit framework: verify every cited external symbol (grep the module source), verify every referenced file exists, check that all spec ACs are covered, check that the prompt has proper stub/fail-loud behavior, check naming conventions, etc.\n\nReturn the full audit report with PASS/FAIL/WARNING for each check category and a summary verdict.","agentId":"a43d9eaae6111237e","agentType":"dark-factory:prompt-auditor","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have enough context to deliver the audit report.\n\n# Prompt Audit Report: 002-spec-001-scanner-gate-and-tests\n\n**File**: `/workspace/prompts/002-spec-001-scanner-gate-and-tests.md`\n**Score**: 4/10\n**Status**: Significant Issues — Multiple critical blockers prevent execution\n\n## Critical Context Finding\n\nThe entire prompt rests on the assumption that prompt 1 (`/workspace/prompts/001-spec-001-